      "type": "header",
      "level": 1,
      "text": "Scrub Typhus"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Scrub typhus is caused by Orientia tsutsugamushi and is transmitted by chiggers (larval mites). It is endemic in Southeast Asia, the Indian subcontinent, and northern Australia."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Clinical Manifestations"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Clinical features include fever, headache, myalgia, and a characteristic eschar at the site of the chigger bite. A maculopapular rash may also be present."
    },
    {
      "type": 'header',
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Diagnosis"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "text": "Diagnosis is based on clinical presentation and can be confirmed with serological tests (IFA) or PCR."
    },
    {
      "type": "header",
      "level": 2,
      "text": "Treatment"
    },
    {
